:: Aftermath {"position":"2300,500","size":"100,100"}
The next morning feels quieter.

Not because anything has settled. Just because there's less left to say.

You get there a little later than you meant to.

The car is gone. The garage is open. The space looks smaller without anything in it.

There are people outside. Not as many as yesterday, but enough that you don't have to ask what's happening.

Samael is standing near the entrance.

Two officers with him.

He's not fighting. Not arguing. Just standing there, shoulders tight, looking somewhere past everyone instead of at them.

Someone near you says his name under their breath.

One of the officers is talking, something about procedure, about statements, about what happens next. It all sounds like it's already been decided.

Samael nods at something you don't hear.

They move him toward the car.

No one stops them.

Abby is there.

Off to the side, not part of it, not separate either. Watching like everyone else. When someone speaks to her, she answers. Calm. Measured. Like she has been.

The car door closes.

The engine starts.

People begin talking again before it even pulls away.

Like it's already done.

[[You stayed where you were->Judgment]]


:: E-A-0 {"position":"1500,200","size":"100,100"}
(set: $viewed to it + (a: "EA"))
(set: $saw_abby_rewrite to true)

Abby is already talking when you tune in.

Not loudly. Just steady.

"It's been a long day," she says. "For all of us."

Someone makes a small sound of agreement. Glass shifts on the table.

"Last night too," she adds. "We were all running on nothing by the end of it."

Cassandra nods. "Yeah."

Abby glances toward Samael, then back to the group. "David especially. He could barely keep his eyes open."

A couple people murmur agreement.

Abby leans back slightly. "I should've told him to just go home."

No one picks that up.

After a second, like it's just something that came back to her, she says, "Sam, you had me grab something for him, didn't you? On my way back."

Samael looks up. "I-" He hesitates. "Yeah. I just thought... maybe it would help him sleep."

"Right," Abby says.

The conversation moves on.

[[You stayed with the group a while longer->Evening-Bottleneck]]


:: E-B-0 {"position":"1500,400","size":"100,100"}
(set: $viewed to it + (a: "EB"))

Samael is sitting a little apart from the others.

Not far enough to leave, just far enough that no one has to look at him unless they want to. There's a drink in his hand he hasn't touched in a while. He keeps turning it slowly, like he's trying to remember why he picked it up.

When someone talks to him, he answers. Too quickly, like he's been waiting for the question. When no one does, he just sits there, staring at nothing in particular.

You end up near him without really deciding to.

"You okay?" you ask.

"Yeah," he says immediately. Then, after a second, "I mean, yeah. Just... weird day."

He lets out a short breath, something that might have been a laugh earlier. "I keep thinking about this morning. Like I missed something. You know?"

Before you can answer, Abby's voice cuts in, soft but direct.

"Sam, can I grab you for a second?"

He looks up at her like he wasn't expecting it, then nods too fast. "Yeah. Yeah, sure."

She gestures toward the kitchen, or maybe just somewhere out of the way. Not far. Still in the same space, just not part of the circle.

They step off together.

You can still hear the rest of the room behind you, people talking over each other, glasses moving, something playing low in the background.

You could follow them. It wouldn't be hard.

Or you could stay where you are.

* [[Follow them, quietly->E-B-1]]
* [[Stay with the group->E-B-2]]


:: E-B-1 {"position":"1600,400","size":"100,100"}
(set: $saw_A_influence_B to true)
(set: $clues_found to it + 1)

You give it a second, then drift after them.

Not close. Just enough to stay out of the room they're moving into. The hallway carries sound better than it should.

Abby's voice comes first.

"—no, it's fine," she says, low, even. "Just keep it simple."

Samael says something you don't catch.

A pause.

"Don't add anything," Abby says. "You don't need to explain it. You just asked me to grab something. That's all."

Another pause. Longer.

"I know," she adds, quieter. "You're okay."

You hear Samael exhale, shaky. "I didn't— I mean, I wasn't—"

"I know," Abby says again, cutting across it. Not sharp. Just enough.

Silence, for a moment.

Then, softer, "Just stick to that."

Footsteps shift. Closer.

You step back before they come out.

By the time they return to the room, Samael looks different. Not better, exactly. Just... steadier.

Like he knows what he's supposed to say.

[[You went back to the group->Evening-Bottleneck]]


:: E-B-2 {"position":"1600,500","size":"100,100"}
You stay where you are.

The conversation around you keeps moving, uneven, people picking up threads and dropping them just as quickly. Someone is trying to remember what time everyone left. Someone else is talking about the ticket again, like saying it out loud might make it feel real.

Samael and Abby come back a minute later.

You almost miss the change. He's still tense, still not quite looking anyone in the eye, but when someone speaks to him now, he doesn't hesitate the same way.

"Yeah," he says, when someone asks him something you don't quite catch. "Yeah, that's what happened."

He takes a drink this time. Not much, just enough to have something to do with his hands.

Abby settles back into the group like she was never gone.

Whatever they talked about doesn't come up again.

[[You stayed with the group a while longer->Evening-Bottleneck]]


:: E-C-0 {"position":"1500,600","size":"100,100"}
(set: $viewed to it + (a: "EC"))
(set: $heard_abby_errand to true)

"...no, because that's what I'm saying," Cassandra is already in the middle of it when you tune in. "Everyone was there when it hit. Right? Like, we all saw it."

Someone across from her nods. "Yeah."

"And then it just-" she makes a small motion with her hand, like something scattering, "-everyone kind of split off."

She's not really looking at anyone. Just trying to hold onto the sequence.

"I remember David was still around for a bit. After. He was-" she pauses, searching for it, "-he was in a good mood. Everyone was."

A couple quiet agreements.

She frowns slightly. "Then I went to grab my stuff. I think."

Another pause.

"And I passed the break room, and Abby and Sam were in there. Talking about something." She shakes her head a little. "I didn't really catch it."

She turns her glass slowly on the table.

"I don't think I saw her after that," she says.

It doesn't land like anything. Just part of trying to remember.

"Not until this morning, I mean."

Someone else starts talking before she can add anything else.

[[You listened until the conversation shifted->E-C-1]]


:: E-C-1 {"position":"1600,600","size":"100,100"}
You could pull her back to it.

Or let it move on.

* [[Ask her about Abby->E-C-2]]
* [[Let it go->Evening-Bottleneck]]


:: E-C-2 {"position":"1600,700","size":"100,100"}
(set: $clues_found to it + 1)

"Wait," you say. "You didn't see Abby after that?"

Cassandra looks up, like she has to rewind a second to figure out what you mean.

"After the break room?" she asks.

You nod.

She thinks for a moment, slower this time.

"I mean... no, I don't think so," she says. "She was there when the numbers came up, and then—" she makes that same small motion with her hand, people scattering, "—everyone kind of split."

She frowns slightly.

"And she just... went, I guess. Pretty quick."

Another pause.

"I remember thinking it was a little weird she didn't stick around, but—" she shrugs, dismissing it even as she says it, "—people were moving around. I figured she went to grab something."

She looks back down at her glass.

"It didn't seem like anything."

The conversation around you keeps going, like nothing was ever interrupted.

[[You let it drop->Evening-Bottleneck]]


:: E-D-0 {"position":"1500,800","size":"100,100"}
(set: $viewed to it + (a: "ED"))

You step back from the table.

It doesn't take much. Just a few feet, enough that you're not part of any one conversation anymore. The room settles into something easier to watch from a distance.

People talk in pieces. Someone starts a thought, someone else finishes a different one. Glasses move. Someone laughs at the wrong time and then stops.

Abby is almost always near Samael.

Not directly. Not hovering. Just close enough that when someone looks his way, she's there too.

A hand on his shoulder for a second. A quiet word you don't quite catch. Small shifts that keep him from getting pulled too far into anything.

(if: $saw_A_influence_B)[
You start to notice the pattern.

The way he answers. The way she steps in just before he has to. Like he's following something, and she's keeping it from slipping.
]

(if: not ($saw_A_influence_B))[
They just seem... close. More than they usually are, maybe. Hard to tell if that means anything.
]

Nothing stays in focus for long.

[[You went back to the group->Evening-Bottleneck]]


:: End-Insight {"position":"2900,500","size":"100,100"}
You don't leave it alone.

Samael, taken away. An explanation that should be enough.

It doesn't hold.

You turn it back over, slower this time. Not trying to make it fit. Just letting it sit where it lands.

The pills. Bought, gone, left behind.

Abby leaving early. Before anyone else had time to react.

Samael repeating something that didn't sound like it came from him.

None of it proves anything.

It stops feeling separate.

You don't say it. There's nothing to say it to that would make it real for anyone else.

The version that stays is quieter than that.

Not just Samael.

The office moves on the same way it would have anyway. Conversations settle. The story hardens into something clean enough to keep.

You let it happen.

There isn't anything else to do.

Time passes.

The ticket never comes up again. Not seriously. Not in a way that goes anywhere.

Then, later—

Not right away. Long enough that it doesn't feel connected unless you're already looking for it—

You hear about Abby.

She leaves. Nothing dramatic. Just… stops showing up one week and doesn't come back the next.

Someone mentions it in passing. A new job. Something better.

You see her once after that.

Not close. Not enough to talk.

Just enough.

She looks like someone things worked out for.

It settles the same way everything else did.

No one else seems to notice.

You do.

You leave it there.

[[Start again->Start]]


:: End-Joke {"position":"2500,200","size":"100,100"}
You leave it there.

Samael, taken away. An explanation that fits, and you don't ask anything more of it.

You step off the curb without looking.

There is no manhole cover where it should be.

The rest of the day ends there.

[[Start again->Start]]


:: End-Surface {"position":"2700,700","size":"100,100"}
You leave it there.

Samael, taken away. An explanation that fits. Not perfectly, but enough.

People talk about it for a while. At work, at home, anywhere it comes up. The same pieces, passed around until they settle into something everyone can agree on.

He was there. He stayed late. He found the body.

It doesn't take much to make that into a story.

The rest of it fades.

The office opens again a few days later. Slower at first. Quieter. Then less so. People stop lowering their voices when they say his name. Then they stop saying it at all.

No one mentions the ticket anymore.

You catch yourself thinking about it once or twice. Not the details, just the shape of it. How it all lined up.

It holds.

Well enough.

Things move on.

You do too.

[[Start again->Start]]


:: End-Uncertain {"position":"2700,300","size":"100,100"}
You try to leave it there.

Samael, taken away. An explanation that should be enough.

It almost is.

People talk about it the same way they always do. The details settle into place, the rough edges worn down until nothing catches anymore. It becomes something you can repeat without thinking too hard about it.

You find yourself doing the same.

He stayed late. He was there in the morning. He found the body.

It holds, if you don't look at it for too long.

Every so often, something pulls at it. A detail that doesn't quite sit where it should. Something said, something remembered, something that felt right at the time and doesn't now.

It never turns into anything.

You let it go.

The office opens again. People fall back into routine. Conversations shift. The night stops coming up unless someone forces it.

You move with it.

Whatever didn't fit stays that way.

[[Start again->Start]]


:: Evening {"position":"1300,500","size":"100,100"}
The police didn't stay long.

They asked questions, wrote things down, moved through the office like they were checking boxes off a list, and then they were gone. No one told you what they thought. No one told you what happens next. Just a quiet understanding that whatever this was, it wasn't finished.

Hours passed. You don't remember most of them.

At some point, someone suggested getting together. Not the office. Somewhere else. A living room, a bar, it doesn't really matter. Just somewhere that wasn't that garage, that car, that smell still stuck in the back of your throat.

Now you're all here, or what's left of you.

Drinks sit half-finished on the table. Someone put music on and then turned it down so low it might as well not be there. People are talking, but not about the same things. Conversations overlap, break, pick back up somewhere else.

You catch pieces of it, but never all at once.

Where do you listen first?

* [[Abby, already talking->E-A-0]]
* [[Samael, holding together just barely->E-B-0]]
* [[Cassandra, trying to hold onto it->E-C-0]]
* [[Step back and watch the room->E-D-0]]


:: Evening-Bottleneck {"position":"1900,500","size":"100,100"}
The night doesn't stay in one piece.

You can catch parts of it. Conversations that made sense while you were in them.

They don't line up when you try to hold onto more than one.
