:: M-A-0 {"position":"700,200","size":"100,100"}
(set: $viewed to it + (a: "MA"))

You were still in the parking lot when Abby's car pulled in, later than it should have been, later than anyone else had been that morning. She got out fast, the way people get out of cars when they already know something is wrong, and the door stayed open behind her for a second like she'd forgotten it. She didn't say anything about being late. Nobody asked.

(live: 3s)[(stop:)She took one look at the open garage bay and her whole face did the thing faces do when they're deciding to be useful instead of falling apart. She put a hand on your arm, brief, firm, grounding, the way you'd steady someone at a funeral, and then she was moving. She got her phone out. She made the call you hadn't made. Her voice on the line was low and clear and she said the address twice without being asked, because of course she did. You stood there listening to her say the words "unresponsive" and "enclosed space" and felt the small, ugly relief of not having to be the one saying them.)]

(live: 8s)[(stop:)When she was off the phone she came back to where you were standing. Her eyes were wet but not spilling, held right at the edge of it, and she said "poor David" in a voice so quiet you almost missed it, and then almost in the same breath she said "and poor Sam, God, can you imagine, can you imagine being the one to walk in on that." She looked over at Samael where he was still standing by the car, hands in his pockets now, not moving. "He's going to carry this," she said. "He's going to carry this for a long time."

What did you ask her?

|choices>[
(link: "About Samael")[
(replace: ?choices)[]
(replace: ?answer)[You asked her if she thought Sam was okay. She shook her head slowly, watching him across the lot, and said "no, no he's not, nobody would be, he's the kind of person who takes things like this personally even when there's no reason to." She squeezed your arm again. "We should keep an eye on him today. All of us. Okay?" You said okay. There wasn't anything else to say.

(live: 15s)[(stop:)Whatever you'd asked, she ended up in the same place, steady and sad and already three steps ahead of the rest of you. She told you someone should probably start calling families. She said she'd do it if nobody else wanted to. She said it like she was volunteering for a chore, not a terrible thing, and somehow that made it easier to let her.

By the time the sirens started in the distance she had already herded the four of you into something that looked like a group, and you realized you were standing closer to the others than you had been a minute ago without remembering moving. That was Abby. That was how Abby worked. By the time you noticed what she was doing it was already done and you were grateful for it.

[[You let her take care of it->Morning-Bottleneck]]]
]]
<br>
(link: "About last night")[
(replace: ?choices)[]
(replace: ?answer)[You asked her about last night, about the ticket, about how everyone had seemed when they left. She let out a long breath and gave a small, sad smile. "He was happy," she said. "That's the thing I keep coming back to. He was so happy. He kept laughing at nothing. You remember? He kept laughing and laughing and I thought, good, he deserves a night like this." She shook her head. "God. God, I'm glad he had that. At least he had that."

(live: 15s)[(stop:)Whatever you'd asked, she ended up in the same place, steady and sad and already three steps ahead of the rest of you. She told you someone should probably start calling families. She said she'd do it if nobody else wanted to. She said it like she was volunteering for a chore, not a terrible thing, and somehow that made it easier to let her.

By the time the sirens started in the distance she had already herded the four of you into something that looked like a group, and you realized you were standing closer to the others than you had been a minute ago without remembering moving. That was Abby. That was how Abby worked. By the time you noticed what she was doing it was already done and you were grateful for it.

[[You let her take care of it->Morning-Bottleneck]]]
]]
<br>
(link: "About the ticket")[
(replace: ?choices)[]
(replace: ?answer)[You asked her about the ticket, hating yourself a little for asking, because it felt like the wrong question to ask in a parking lot with a dead man twenty feet away. She didn't look bothered. She just nodded like of course you were asking, of course somebody had to. "I don't know," she said. "I haven't thought about it. I mean, I've thought about it, you can't not, but I haven't thought about it. That's a problem for later. That's a problem for when we're allowed to have problems again." She gave you a tired half smile. "Right?"

(live: 15s)[(stop:)Whatever you'd asked, she ended up in the same place, steady and sad and already three steps ahead of the rest of you. She told you someone should probably start calling families. She said she'd do it if nobody else wanted to. She said it like she was volunteering for a chore, not a terrible thing, and somehow that made it easier to let her.

By the time the sirens started in the distance she had already herded the four of you into something that looked like a group, and you realized you were standing closer to the others than you had been a minute ago without remembering moving. That was Abby. That was how Abby worked. By the time you noticed what she was doing it was already done and you were grateful for it.

[[You let her take care of it->Morning-Bottleneck]]]
]]
]
|answer>[]
